t_tokens": 859, "total_tokens": 859}, "id": "53bc536d-d2f3-914c-8815-9d0232889846"}, "input": {"input": ["AMERICAN PSYCHIATRIC ASSOCIATION:The American Psychiatric Association is the organization that developed the DSM system for diagnosing mental disorders, including the introduction of the multi-axial diagnostic principle in DSM-III in 1980>", "WORLD HEALTH ORGANIZATION:The World Health Organization (WHO) is a pivotal international body dedicated to global health, encompassing a wide range of initiatives and responsibilities. In 1969, WHO defined rehabilitation as the comprehensive and coordinated application of medical, educational, social, vocational, and other measures aimed at helping disabled individuals regain or improve their functions and quality of life. This definition underscores WHO's commitment to holistic health care and support for individuals with disabilities.\n\nWHO has also been instrumental in addressing mental health issues. In 1997, the organization reported that 20%-30% of undiagnosed patients in general hospitals have mental health issues, while 15%-20% of diagnosed patients have psychiatric problems. This finding highlights the critical need for mental health screening and intervention in non-psychiatric clinical settings. Additionally, WHO has conducted research revealing differences in the diagnosis of mental disorders across various cultural backgrounds and clinicians, emphasizing the importance of culturally sensitive approaches in mental health care.\n\nAs the international body responsible for the International Classification of Diseases (ICD) system, WHO plays a crucial role in classifying diseases and health problems globally, including mental disorders. This system provides a standardized framework for diagnosing and understanding health conditions worldwide. Furthermore, WHO provides global statistics on suicide rates and trends, drawing attention to the increasing prevalence of suicide and the urgent need for effective prevention strategies.\n\nThrough its diverse initiatives, WHO continues to address critical health issues, promote mental health awareness, and provide essential resources and frameworks for global health improvement.", "CHINESE MEDICAL ASSOCIATION PSYCHIATRIC BRANCH:The Chinese Medical Association Psychiatric Branch is the organization responsible for developing the CCMD system, which classifies and diagnoses mental disorders in China, incorporating cultural and traditional considerations>", "DSM-III:The DSM-III is the third edition of the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, published by the American Psychiatric Association in 1980, which introduced the multi-axial diagnostic system>", "CCMD:The CCMD (Chinese Classification and Diagnostic Criteria of Mental Disorders) is a system developed by the Chinese Medical Association Psychiatric Branch to classify and diagnose mental disorders in China>", "MOOD DISORDERS:Mood disorders, including depression and bipolar disorder, are classified under ICD-10, DSM-IV, and CCMD-3 as mental disorders affecting emotional states>", "精神活性物质所致精神障碍:\"精神活性物质所致精神障碍\" (Mental Disorders Due to Psychoactive Substances) is a category of mental health conditions directly caused by the use of psychoactive substances. These substances include, but are not limited to, alcohol, opioids, cannabis, and other drugs that alter brain function. The disorders can manifest as either acute or chronic mental health problems, depending on the duration and intensity of substance use. Acute issues may arise shortly after substance intake, while chronic problems develop over prolonged exposure. This classification encompasses a range of psychological and behavioral disturbances linked to the effects of psychoactive substances on the central nervous system, highlighting the significant impact of substance use on mental well-being.", "非成瘾物质所致精神障碍:A category of mental disorders caused by non-addictive substances, such as carbon monoxide, organic compounds, heavy metals, and food>", "脑外伤所致精神障碍:A mental disorder caused by brain injuries>", "脑瘤所致精神障碍:A mental disorder caused by brain tumors>"], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-v3"}}}